,Not Recommended,322500,22126306,"Posted: 29 March, 2016",all,TＯＭＭＹ ＷＩＳＥAu,"Superhot is possibly the most disappointing game I’ve played so far this year. It’s got a great premise with it’s time bending matrix style mechanics, but to be perfectly honest with you that’s all it’s got going for it.Now for those of you unfamiliar with the title, Superhot is a first person shooter where time moves only as you do… remember those fight sequences in 300… now imagine them with guns and you’ve got superhot – a never before seen melting pot of both strategic and twitch based shooting.Now of course bullet time isn’t really a new thing and over the years we’ve been inundated with enough Max Payne and F.E.A.R clones to be sick of the concept. However, it’s never really had any use beyond doing John Woo’esque dives to look cool and break up the otherwise monotonous game loop. Heck if you’re name’s Dereck and you enjoy filing tax returns you could probably get through Max Payne without using bullet time once.The difference with superhot is that the games mechanics actually force you to choreograph some really impressive stunts just to stay alive. It’s a bit like hotline Miami where getting hit once causes instant death forcing the player to make split second decisions to stand a chance in a firefight. Infact it’s a lot like hotline Miami with throwable objects used to stun enemies and block bullets, and very similar melee and projectile weapons.The only real difference in terms of gameplay is hotline’s top down all-seeing perspective compared with Superhot’s much more limited first person view, a limitation in theory meant to balance out the bullet time… In practice I’ve been shot in the back countless times by enemies behind me. It feels cheap and annoying and it’s one of the major problems I have with the gameplay.It also feels like the dev’s either didn’t know or didn’t care about this problem when they created their replay system, kilstagram. The idea behind it is that, after you’ve cleared each level, you get to watch a replay of you dispatching your enemies in real time which you get the option to upload to various social media sites. You know because all those nightclub photographs you got tagged in weren’t enough to show people how much fun you were having without them.Anyway on paper it sounds like a pretty cool idea – the chance for you to show off your Wachowskii’esque bullet time skills but in reality the played back footage looks more like that of a twitchy counterstrike player as you keep glancing behind you to make sure you don’t get flanked causing the camera to spin back and forth making it headache inducing to watch… actually that does sound a lot like a wachowskii film.Aaaand that’s it… well at least in terms of mechanics… and to be honest with you it all feels very lackluster. For all it borrows from Hotline Miami, I kinda wish they’d taken more. At the moment there simply isn’t any reward for combos or difficult kills like headshots, there isn’t even any music in the background which makes it feel more like an early access title than anything else. But I guess that’s the kind of aesthetic they were going for – everything in the game is made up of plain textures with a really minimalist color scheme.  And it also ties in with the story the dev’s wanted to tell… that’s right the dev’s actually managed to come up with a story to tie all of this together, though as you’ll see it’s so phoned in and half-arsed it feels more like it’s there for the sake of having a story.Remember Pony island? Good Neither does the guy that wrote this drivel.  Instead of being a story within Superhot’s universe, it’s a story about playing superhot. You start off the game looking at a dos style operating system when suddenly you get an instant message from a friend sending you a file titled “superhot.exe”. After playing a few levels, the system detects you and it pans out exactly as you’d expect it to be with the system trying to stop the player and the player finding loopholes and backdoor routes to evade the system.  The problem with the narrative is that it does not compliment the gameplay – you could replace the shooting segments with Tetris and the story would still work.It’s a prime example of what people who like to use big words to sound clever call Ludonarative Dissonance, where the gameplay and story don’t match and the exposition just feels like a hindrance to the actual meat of the game.Whilst I can kind of get over the mediocre storyline, the thing I find unforgivable is the 2-hour campaign length. That’s right, you can beat the game in a single sitting! Now I’m not saying all short games are bad, in fact titles like Portal have been praised for not overstaying their welcome with their shot length. The problem with Superhot being so short is that instead of leaving me wanting more, I just feel unsatisfied by the finished product.To rub it in, the dev’s have had a working prototype since 2013 which featured quite a few of the levels that ended up in the full game, most of which was made in a few days at a game jam. It can’t be so hard to make a level that the team could only pump out 20 or so short levels in 3 years! Especially with backing and e3 coverage by both Sony and Microsoft. To have the balls to demand 17 quid (that’s the equivalent of 3 copies of Undertale) for a game that can be beaten in an afternoon is a little bit insulting. Granted there’s more to it than just the campaign, there’s also the arena mode where you have to fend off endless waves of enemies which gets boring after about an hour and there’s the challenge mode where you’ll have to play the campaign meeting certain conditions (for example only using the katana). Like the story, both these additional modes feel last minute and tacked on.The best analogy I have for the game as a whole is to imagine the first chapter of id software’s doom being sold full price. Back in its heyday in the 90’s nobody had ever seen anything like DOOM and I can safely say the gameplay of superhot is just as innovative. However, whilst the game that’s there is relatively enjoyable, albeit flawed, it just ends before the more interesting experimental stages (like in the 3rd act of doom) get to be shown. Ultimately I can’t really recommend picking up the game unless it’s heavily discounted and, to go with the analogy, the game receives a John Romero out of 10. It showed a lot of promise in it’s early days as a prototype, started getting full of itself at e3 and then ultimately♥♥♥♥♥♥the bed with one fell daikatanaesque swoop."
