76561198009156462,Not Recommended,322500,21489732,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Ces,"I've been back and forth on this review. Throughout the day, and through running arguments with fans of the game, I have come to ask ""Was I wrong about SuperHot? Did I simply not appreciate its genius? Have I been letting a bad experience partially related to mobile hardware ruin my opinion of an otherwise sound game?""The answer is no.The reason I cannot reccomend superhot is simple. It is a lazy product, especially at its base pricetag of 25 dollars.- Combat is one dimensional. Your arsenal consists of 3 samey guns and a melee attack, to be used on one basic enemy type, using two AI scripts. All guns shoot slow bullets with overlarge hitboxes that kill enemies wherever they hit them. Combat itself just boils down ""click on the nearest enemy."" There's no strategy, risk/reward, or anything else, because the only thing that makes enemies remotely dangerous is proximity.- The presentation is bland and empty. While visually functional, which is extremely important and should be lauded, there was zero meaningful artistic effort put into this game. Yes, the polygon men shatter and ragdoll nicely, but what does this mean to the narrative, the world? Nothing. The story as well is a vapid copypasta of late 90's cyber-angst so lazy I quit 60% of the way through the game and just looked it up on wikipedia. I was still disappointed.- The playtesting was lackluster. Bullet on bullet collissions, a cool idea on paper, happen so often they become a frustration. I didn't even play a full hour and had it happen to me 5 times. It happened so often that I started to hate it happening, and that's too often. If enemies were actively shooting my bullets down, I might credit it as some modicum of AI intelligence, but no, all were just stupid accidents resulting from center-of-mass shots on enemies that were shooting back. But if this is bad, then level hitboxing is even worse. I had a bullet disappear in midair because it hit an invisible corner, and it was a perfect shot too. You're telling me they spent two and a half years on barely 150 minutes worth of content and couldn't polish the collision?Really, at the end of the day, it doesn't feel like SuperHotTeam even tried when they made this game. Two and a half years ago, SuperHot was a proof-of-concept demo being debuted at 7 day FPS Challenge. Today, it is still a proof-of-concept demo that now goes for 25 dollars. Maybe when they decide to make an actual game it'll be worth it, but for now take your money and go buy a game from a developer who cares."
