76561198019533570,Not Recommended,322500,21489824,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Balrog Son of Nelgar,"This is one of those times when Steam needs a ""meh"" option.For those who haven't followed the 2.5 year long trail of news surrounding this game...SuperHot is a fast-paced fps with a very innovating twist in that time only moves when you do. I see it as a little gimmicky, but in the end, it's well done enough that it's fairly invigorating and just enjoying.However, for 2.5 years, the game has, basically, just been polished with very little in the way of added content. The story will take you about 1.5 hours to 2 hours to complete with the only replayability being the endless mode and challenges (some of which were unfairly difficult). While it is a good game, after a while, it's too repetative with little in the way of actual story (which is just a meta story about how it's not just a game).In terms of price, $25 is waaay to much to ask for this. If you are seriously thinking about purchasing this game, wait until a price drop."
,Not Recommended,322500,21455219,"Posted: 25 February, 2016",all,monster mash,"I don't know what I was expecting. I wasn't super hyped for this game so I went in with what I'd say fairly low expectations. But now that I've fully completed the game, obviously barring challenges and endless mode, I can confidently say this game is the worst waste of time and money ever. About half way through my 2 hour absolute thrill ride (/s) I was already totally fed up of the text simulator that half the game basically is. If I took out all mandatory text scenes in this game it'd be little more than an hour long glorified flash game. Now, the game does offer neat little stuff like 'secrets' hidden in what I presume to be every level, but this has not interested me enough at all to keep me playing, or keep it in my library for that matter.Gunplay is exactly how you'd expect. The whole 'time moves when you move thing' is pretty neat at times. I'm not going to lie, the game definitely has it's entertaining moments, for about 30 minutes, then it becomes frustrating. Hotswitching is fun for the what 5? 6? levels I was allowed to use it in, shame it was introduced too late. The level design is either sixty or total nought, with some levels making you purposefully die so you can play it again or some levels making you make mistakes because you just want it to be over.The story is not particularly engaging, no spoilers, but it becomes GLARINGLY obvious what you're going to have to end up doing very early on in the game. The story is only advanced by compulsory text sections, which can range from short interactions to taking way, WAY too long. The large flashing text is an effective ""cool"" little feature for a while, then it starts to try way too hard to become intimidating and overbearing, which it fails at by being too frequent and 'obvious'? I guess?Right, one more thing. I'm almost certain this is intentional, and somehow the secrets may be involved? Or maybe I missed things. BUT, the game has an OVERBEARING AWFUL LACK OF CHOICE. I seriously get the vibe the devs were going for, but man, is this game linear. It's painfully restrictive, if you're the curious type who tries to look for every way out of being told what to do, this game will be little more than a masochistic experience for you. Again, this may be all irrelevant with game elements which I have not explored.Ultimately, not a good experience. Forgive my ignorance, but I honestly don't know what the devs were doing all those years. If you're a big fan of short games, and LOVE the mechanic of time moving when you do and are willing to play the game well into the challenges and endless mode, go right ahead, seriously, you will have a blast. But to the average player? I wouldn't. The game is good, but very slow paced, and the (unskippable!) text sections go on way too long."
,Not Recommended,322500,26364146,"Posted: 1 November, 2016",all,TheGhostThatWas,"When I say""SUPERHOT IS THE MOST INNOVATIVE SHOOTER I'VE PLAYED IN YEARS!""I mean that. However, before you purchase the game, I should warn you about the numerous problems that the game has. YouSHOULDget SUPERHOT, but let me give you a few warnings first.SUPERHOT's defining feature is that time only moves when you do. This isn't entirely true, astime still moves slowly when you're not moving.This isn't exactly a problem, because if you're taking that long to think which way to dodge a bullet, chances are you deserve to get hit anyway.Short StoryThe game's campaign is very interesting and spooky, but can be beaten inbetween 2-3 hours depending on how well you do, and somevariables. The variables I'll cover in the next section.VariablesIn slow motion, you can almost always tell when you are going to die, and from where. However, some levels contain randomly generated enemies which actually determine whether or not you're going to win. For example, level15HOSPIT.lvlis easily one of the hardest levels to beat simply because after you kill the wave of red guys, several red guys spawn with random guns, ranging from bare handed to shotgun, all in a tight little room. It's unfortunate to say this, but winning some levels like this,especiallyduring challenges and time trials, might only depend on if you're lucky enough to play when all the red guys spawn with only pistols.It is incredibly frustrating that the only way to beat a level is based on whether or not certain enemies spawn, and winning has less to nothing to do with the players skill.The other variable is shotgun fire. Those guns are impossible to predict.The Game BreakersSUPERHOT has a few bugs which can make the game a bit more challenging, to occasionally stopping you from winning a level.Going back to the level15HOSPIT.lvl, there's a good example of a challenging bug. After you enter the first room from the balcony-catwalk-thing, your in the line of fire of a shotgunner and a machine gunner. Your options include running straight at them, or backing up around the corner. However, backing up is a problem because there's a small height difference between the ledge and the room, which prevents you from backing up. And as long as you hold the ""S"" key, the bullets move closer and closer. Jumping over this is out of the question, because as long as your in the air, time continues to move as gravity pulls on you. Little details like this become major problems in Challenge modes. And this isn't the only example of bad world geometry, as some levels have invisible barriers that prevent you from exiting the line of fire altogether.Another good example is the broken Time Trial mode. In at least one level (there may be others, I don't know yet), the timer starts counting before you even finish loading in, resulting in you starting with roughly .97 seconds already passed. This sounds minor, but when the goal is set at 4 seconds, losing that time is almost a quarter of what you should have. On that level, which is03CORRID.lvl, the best possible time I've managed is 4.07, and that was after nearly 20 minutes of retries, on what is only the third level in the game.ConclusionSUPERHOT is very unique and memorable for it's mechanics. It could have been improved during development by adding more levels to the story, but that's only an issue if you don't want to pay full price for that much.The only thing that keeps SUPERHOT from being ""super cool"" is the obvious missed steps taken in testing the game, but development is still semi-active so the game might be fixed in the future.I only hope that the developers are listening to bug reports, and are willing to fix the small stuff. After the game isn't broken enough that I stop raging at trying to complete it 100%, I'll give it my thumbs up.Plus I hope this game gets a Steam Workshop. That would be pretty neat."
