as too little content to critisise more than your average item to critisise.And what else is there to really nitpick? The game looks pretty enough. But why settle for nitpicking? Surely there's a huge bloody problem in this game, a problem which I am veryangry over and wish I wasn't angry over because I could probably fix this myself over the weekend and the developers aren't going to spend 12 minutes to fix this problem? But, whatif I told you, that... THERE IS A PROBLEM LIKE THAT!Yes, believe it or not Superhot has one gaping flaw. It sucks on controller. I tried playing this with my Xbox 360 controller recently, and it was infuriating to the point of regretting anyonebuying this on console. This is one of the worst button layouts I've ever seen, by the way. It controls fine, if not perfectly on keyboard and mouse, but once you start using a controller...Oh boy.Get this, to pick things up, you press the [A]/[x] button. Kinda annoying, but fine.To shoot guns, you press the [A]/[x] button. What? Ok, that's really annoying, but whatever.To throw things, you press the [A]/[x] button.WHATTHEACTUALFAMILYFRIENDLYSWEARWORDSUBSTITUTE?!?!This means, that to throw a melee weapon, you have to be standing out of range of hitting someone with it, even if there are 2 people, both with double barrelled shotguns in your face.Which, I just want to point out; HAPPENS ALL THE TIME. To make matters worse, its a first person shooter, so you'll have one thumb on the left analog stick, and another on the rightanalog stick, and you expect most buttons to be the bumper and trigger buttons. But they're not.So to do anything, you have to awkwardly take your thumb off of the bloody right analog stick, move it up to the buttons, press them (Which by the way has around 1 second of input lag,because of course if does) press it several times because input lag, and then move it back, which will take ages so your target may have been moved, or shot you dead.Woah.I think we've all learned a valuable lesson here. That lesson being, if a game is released first on PC, and designed for PC, assume it WON'T or will have REALLY BAD controllersupport.And if it's released first on console, and designed for console, never get it on PC. I remember the Batman: Arkham Knight PC port like yesterday.I still really wanna play that.But they did patch it, so it's fixed.Continuing with the tide of negetive things, there's also a severe problem that everyone who bought this game will have. A lack of content. There's only around 20 hours of game here,if you wanna complete it, but they are adding new things! Soon! Free content patches galore, god these Devs care about us! (Except it took this game around 2 years to be developed,and this content patch coming soon around 1year and a 1/2 to even get announced. And the maps look so easy to make, just white rooms with black props, windows and red enemies.Give this game mod support already!And we've also learned a valuable lesson just now!That being, this game gets a good 7.5/10.Because it's awesome, but that controller support really sucks, and so does that lack of content. I've gotten more content out of this: [Show One Finger Death Punch]And that's really how you should describe superhot. It's awesome, but it does have flaws. Big ones. But that's just me, I didn't get much content out of the game, but I had a blast with it.If you like this style of game, you'll keep playing, it's the same things I keep saying about One Finger Death Punch, Super Hexagon, Nidhogg, Downwell and now; Superhot. Then again,that price tag is very asky. At least all the ones I just listed were all under £5."
