,Not Recommended,322500,21647114,"Posted: 5 March, 2016",all,Rachsauce,"SuperHot tries to advertise itself as a John Woo simulator, where time slows down through your gun battles and allows you to plot out your actions play-by-play. But the entire game is designed as a twitch shooter, and without sensory cues of where enemies are like footsteps and voices due to the entire game being drowned out by a ""wind tunnel"" effect apparently caused by the slow motion, and the entire color pallet being black, white, and red you're constantly being snuck up on by people and getting killed with a single shot that grazes your shoulder. And of course, despite every other ""twitch shooter"" in existence, the game requires you to (for some reason) lead every single one of your shots and determine where your enemy is moving. This would be all well and good if you had a sniper rifle a few hundred yards away, but this is handguns and assault rifles with enemies no more than thirty to fifty feet away.So it's a twitch shooter that requires you to precisely aim shots and know where your enemies are while you're lacking one of your basic human senses. And to top it all off, the plot is only about an hour and a half long, so congratulations, if you purchased SuperHot you spent $20 for a two-hour long frustrationfest with clunky gameplay and a useless ""gimmick"" that tries to sell itself as innovative. And the plot, which I will not spoil (just watch a Lets Play or walkthrough) is INCREDIBLY pretentious, to Matrix levels, throwing out random bits of plot that just shove the message of the game right in your face, a message we've seen a million times since computers became a mainstream appliance, and the game acts like it's so smart. And the ending literally tells you to tell your friends the game is ""the most innovative shooter you've ever played."" No, I'm serious, it tells you, to your face after the ending, to try to sell the game to your friends by saying it's innovative and awesome. Don't buy this game, put the $20 towards something with ACTUAL innovation and gameplay that wasn't designed by someone trying to be artsy and ""deep."""
