,Recommended,322500,22014631,"Posted: 23 March, 2016",all,Satire is Dead,"[Encourage Memes]I HAVE MIXED FEELINGS ABOUT SUPER HOT.It's an intro in TO cyberpunk. It gives players of any skill level a unique action-puzzle experience that ends up being a blend of The Matrix meets MKultra if M.K. stood for Manchurian Killer.It's better as an arcade game, and you'll unlock that mode following the completion of the short story campaign. I thought it was a tensionless, droll experience up until about the point where the story began to end, when the levels become much more difficult (when it became fun).There's a lot to get into in too many words, so here was my experience.Spoilers will not be tagged, but I'll try to avoid blatantly spelling it out.Super Hot is all about glamour and if you're a playful gamer, you'll have plenty to do. The campaign is presented very well, but I always felt three steps ahead of the cyberpunk story. It ended at about the point where I thought it should've continued on, but damn it was it ever presented in a visually exciting way. I went on to discover all the game's secrets and that's where the story started to really lose me.""You aren't actually going to reveal anything, I get it, Super Hot."" And then Super Hot's mysterious Red Voice continued on and on with its attitude. I continued to find the secrets because it did answer some of its questions, only for it to conclude with a reward for my dedication, and while I appreciate that it fits back in with the hypnosis/brainwashing angle, I felt as insulted by the game as if it asked me if I wanted to buy more energy, like a freemium game would.The ""secrets"" were ultimately unecessary, since like I said, the majority of the """"secret"""" """"""""answers"""""""" were questions that I'm confident most players solved themselves in the campaign.What a strange path the story took though. I was really into it up until the point where it was clear that the secrets were bunk, and then it got all capitalist on me and threw the punk part of the cyberpunk out the window with the coupon.Still, tho, the game's themes and presentation are intertwined, and I actually do like Killstagram because it ties back into the boldness of their compulsion to make you part of their viral marketing, and even the warez angle feeds into the viral edginess. That stuff is fantastic. Moreover, Killstagram feeds into the playfulness and how much fun you can have by learning that juggling guns and banking thrown objects off walls is the most hilarious and cool looking fun you can have. Killstagram, if you're into it, changes the way you approach the game, turning it into something more creative than clearing the mission.The story is an intro to cyberpunk and posthuman themes though, and its style and tone are its own. I just wish they excluded the ""secrets"" which ruined it pretty handily.So, yes. It's true. The game really starts after the campaign ends. This game is so much more engaging as an arcade game with rules and restrictions. The puzzle aspect really shines when the game becomes challenging, forcing you to think creatively, and even reactively...So yeah, I keep bouncing back and forth on whether or not this game is Super Hot or Over Rated because I keep thinking back to the F.E.A.R. series as one of the big games to use slo-mo in a glamorous way  but I think you'll probably enjoy the game of Super Hot, and if you didn't find it very challenging, keep playing and the intensity will increase through later modes."
