,Recommended,322500,33239138,Posted: 4 July,all,daletfours,"SUPERHOT is a pretty mixed bag. It has the base for what potentially could have been a truly revolutionary first person shooter, but somehow fell short; SUPERHOT is a totally stellar idea with frustratingly underwhelming executiuon, resulting in another one of those niche indie titles that's pretty dang fun, but mindlessly so.Let's start with the good. SUPERHOT's main gimmick is that time will only move normally when you move. When you stand still, time will drop into very slow motion (but it will not stop) allowing you to plan your next move. Everything in the game, including both enemies and yourself, will die from one bullet, or from several consecutive melee attacks. Combining the concepts of time manipulation and swift, quick death, SUPERHOT straddles the line between frantic action and slow, strategic planning. This mix is largely satisfying, and the short levels combined with quick respawn times encourages experimentation and variation. Enemy AI is simple, and the game's difficulty relies more on throwing a bunch of people at you at once rather than clever tactics, but it doesn't detract from SUPERHOT as much as it would in other games. Later in the game you'll pick up the ability to switch bodies, keeping the gameplay fresh for a little while longer. At the end of every level, you can watch your replay at full speed to see what it would look like if SUPERHOT was a regular shooter and you just happened to have superhuman reflexes. The presentation is great too; with a minimalistic artstyle and a story that gets pretty meta on you multiple times over, SUPERHOT leaves you longing for more.Which becomes the game's biggest downfall. It's just too. Damn. Short. I finished the game in 115 minutes, 5 minutes short of Steam's 2 hour limit on refunds. You can play the whole game from start to finish and then get all your money back if you wanted to. And, understandably, had they just added more levels then people probably would have labeled the game as too repetitive. This is the problem with any game that revolves around one simple gimmick. You can only milk it for so long before it gets boring. SUPERHOT is as short as it is because, other than its main gimmick, the game has nothing interesting or unique to offer. Again, it's a fantastic idea...but that's all it is. SUPERHOT probably would have done better if it was labeled as a tech demo for something rather than a full blown game. Completing the game will unlock endless mode, but that doesn't stay fresh for very long. SUPERHOT is an amazing game until it isn't anymore, and then you'll move on to something else. With a playtime of less than 2 hours for the main part of the game, SUPERHOT remains (as of the time of this writing) the same price that it did when it first came out over a year ago: a steep, unfairly priced $25. What I'm about to say is something I haven't really said in any of my other reviews...SUPERHOT is pretty much objectively not worth its current price of $25.I bought this game during Steam's 2017 Summer Sale, for $14.99. That should have been the game's regular price. At full price, you are paying almost half the price of a fully fledged AAA title for a game so short you can easily burn through almost all the content in one sitting. I think that's unacceptable. I am giving SUPERHOT a positive review because its a fun game; very unique in what it offers. But I cannot stress enough thatyou should not pay full price for this game.SUPERHOT is enjoyable, but there is no way in hell that it is worth $25. Not even close."
,Recommended,322500,33218759,Posted: 4 July,all,Infamous,"This is a great game, a blast all the way through, but I don't think it's a fully realized idea quite yet. You see the 1.8 hours I have on record? That's the entire campaign all the way through. That's pretty bad for 25$, but I think the unique experience is worth it IF IT'S ON SALE! The puzzle fps is a fun concept, and the game does so much stuff really well it's hard not to have a blast going through it for the first time.The gameplay is always really fresh and exciting, the punches and headshots and throws feel so satisfying as you learn to lead enemies and have them move into it. You feel like a super hacker badass when you are just gunning and slicing right and left, and the levels are varied and complement the mechanics fantastically. Also, it isn't very linear either, there are a ton of different ways you can go about dispatching your foes, and I feel like it would be interesting to revisit the game later for another playthrough.The ""story"" or fragmented bits that are fed to you is intriguing, and while there isn't a total payoff in the end, it is fun and interesting enough to string you along for the ride. The game takes control of your menu and game at certain points, and ""glitches"" and screws up your graphics for a surreal, drug like experience (never taken drugs, it seems that way though).Overall, this game is fresh, and fun, and interesting, and I felt like if they have another few hours of gameplay with some new abilities gained along the way, this game would be way more worth it. I still recommend it, but DEFINITELY wait for a sale unless you are made of money."
