,Not Recommended,322500,23422078,"Posted: 6 June, 2016",all,Pungent Raindeer King,"I'll open the review by stating plainly: I quite enjoyed my time with this game (though got bored with it after about 17 hours, YMMV). I am giving the game a ""not recommended"" rating specifically because the developer has chosen to make the VR version of the game Oculus exclusive. Hardware exclusivity of the sort console gamers have long since accepted as ""normal"" is NOT ok. It does NOT belong on PC. And I will NOT be supporting this game, any offshoots of it, or the developer unless they change their policy. It's extremely disappointing to see a promising and yes, quite innovative, indie developer take such a consumer-unfriendly route.That said, I should try to give at least a passing review of the game. SUPERHOT is the most innovative shooter I've played in years (truly). The ""story"" or ""campaign"" is odd, and quite short - the real meat of the game lies in the challenge modes. As you probably know if you're reading this review, the central conceit of this game is that time only moves when you move. That's mostly true - time moves at a crawl when you're not moving. As a gameplay gimmick it works quite well. Using the slomo mechanic, you can chain together improbably amazing feats such as throwing a cup at a dude to disarm him, punching a gun out of another dude's hand, grabbing that gun out of midair to shoot the first guy, then dodging three shotgun blasts from another guy so you can grab the katana from the wall (where you threw it a earlier) to cut him in half. Gameplay is really solid and a lot of fun, is what I'm saying.Aesthetically, the game knows what its trying to do and achieves it. The art style is more about making information easily visible and creating a cool-looking world than maximizing visual fidelity, but it works. Look at the screenshots or gameplay video if you want to know more about the art style. I dig it, personally.Performance-wise, I'm somewhat mixed. I run a GTX 760, which is a bit old but should still have zero problems maintaining 60 fps on a game with graphics such as these. Most of the time, that is the case - unless I'm using more than one monitor. For some reason, even though only one of my monitors (the one I'm running the game on) is even plugged into the graphics card, I get very low FPS and stutter whenever I try to play the game with secondary monitors enabled. This doesn't happen often, but I have noticed it in other games such as Enter the Gungeon. In any case, just know that you could run into that problem. Game seems to run fine (for me at least) if I stay in single monitor configuration.All that said - I'd encourage you to look elsewhere for your purchasing decisions as this developer has shown themselves to be more concerned with making a quick buck than doing what is right for consumers. Hardware exclusivity does not belong on the PC platform. Period. I won't lie, it's a good game - but I'd encourage you to not support these kinds of practices. I'll edit this part out if the dev changes their policy on exclusivity, of course."
