76561198039894350,Not Recommended,322500,21554941,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,ben,"Pretty disappointing. I'm not one to write reviews (I believe this is my first), but I do feel somewhat ripped off. I read the favorable RPS review and was impressed that its only a few hundred MB. Despite that, loading times aren't great. That's a big reason I go for indie titles above big studio releases.My biggeest gripe is that this game seems to take itself and its aesthetic way too seriously. A simple menu that doesn't flash static with every transition would be just fine, I don't need THAT much immersion. (I think playing this game on a VR headset would give me brain damage.)The principal mechanic--time moves when you move--actually diminishes the FPS tactics of cover and ambush, since you're rewarded for dodging bullets and your ""plan"" is really just weaving through slow-motion projectiles. I got bored with that after a few levels, and don't foresee any desire to pick it up again. If the interface were a bit more standardized, where I could mess around a bit on each level, I think it might be a fine diversion, but I can't be bothered to wade through the arcane interface to find a playstyle that suits me, instead of playing the shooter on rails that bored me so quickly. All flash and no camera."
,Not Recommended,322500,21468604,"Posted: 25 February, 2016",all,KitKat,"I want to recommend this game.Superhot is an FPS with an interesting and unique premise and that's that time moves when you move. The claim here, however, is false. When one here decides they wish to stop in the face bullets, these bullets continue to move. Men with guns will continue to aim, and brutes oozing to bruise will still turning around after you've decided to jump over them, but very very slowly. So it is then needed to predict not only where everything will end up once time flows normally, but also weither these minor changes will affect your next action.This is inline with the biggest part of the game, which is mental eyeballing of distances of bullets relative to your exterior. An exterior that you don't know the limits of, however. There's no way to judge your own hitbox, other than the idea that if it's not under you or towards the center of your view then you're probably safe, but this is not always the case. This might not seem important, I mean most FPS don't have or need full body awareness, but this game is about Spacial Awareness and I am not aware of my own space. Not to mention most other games I can tank a bullet.One hit kill games need to stop, just saying. Being a slow time badass isn't that fun when in psuedo-stopped time that's a bullet in your face with nothing you can do about it and the grim reapear laughing in your♥♥♥♥♥The deceivingly simple and pretty graphics of the game are amazing, although due to preformance issues I have must feel that something is very taxing in this area. Lastly, the worst thing, and the most deal breaking problem with the entire game is the sound design. There is no music. Straight up, nothing. With some sort of system that either had a time slowed to time not slowed fade in, or a song that sounded good but sped up and slow, this would've been godly. Sadly though without music at times everything feels same-ish and rather tedious as the game occupies only one sense.Pros:-Unique-Pretty-Feel like a badassCons:-Preformance Issues-Short af-No music-Not actual stopped timeIs it worth 25 dollars, no, not at all. The max I would pay for this is 10 dollars, if even."
