,Not Recommended,322500,21577031,"Posted: 1 March, 2016",all,𝓹𝓲𝔃𝔃𝓪𝓹𝓪𝓽,"Superhot is very unique and offers some fun moments, but it's far from a complete game. The story is 2 hours long, and frankly, very boring. I shrugged that off thinking it wouldn't matter much because the combat mechanics are interesting (time stands still when you're not moving, cool right!?), but sadly, the gameplay started to spread thin after a few levels.I guess this fits the plot of the Superhot, since the protasgonist is supposed to be playing a VR game that a friend hacked into before it even hit the alpha phase of development.Here's a short list of my gripes:1) The AI is terrible. The majority of the levels have ""waves"" of enemies, so you'll start a level, clear the room, and wait for another wave or two of enemies to appear. I imagine they implemented this because the level designs are tiny and there isn't really a whole lot of room for a significant amount of enemies to patrol. The only thing indicating that a wave of enemies is approaching is a red glow that appears on doors and doorways. Most of the time you won't notice the red glow, so you're going to die a lot, and only progress through trial and error. This gets very tiring after a while.Enemies either stand still and take a position to shoot at you from afar, or they enter a ""chase mode"" where they run after you, turn corners willy nilly, and find you and shoot you point blank if you're behind cover. After a while you'll learn to expect the AI to do this, and your playstyle will adapt accordingly. This causes the gameplay to stagnate and become incredibly predictable.2) The half♥♥♥♥♥♥♥implementation of a story is terrible, but this is just my creative opinion. If you played this game and the story didn't come off as something a 9th grader wrote in a creative fiction class, then lucky you. I happen to think it completely ruins the aesthetic of Superhot.3) There is no real progression. You unlock the ability to switch into enemies' bodies toward the end of the game, but you'll only use it 5-10 times before the story ends. That's it. You're going to beat every level in the same fashion you did with the last.4) There is no replayabiity. It could benefit from a level timer, level scores and objectives, and a general high score counter. At least with those types of mechanics, players have a reason to return to levels and take different routes.Conclusion:Superhot is cool but it's not worth the price tage of $20+The hype is riding on ONE gimmick: Time stands still when you stand still. It's a really ♥♥♥♥ing cool premise, but it's not very fun if it's implemented in an incomplete game. I personally think each and every one of us is entitled to ask for more from the devs. We don't deserve to have♥♥♥♥♥♥like this released for $20+, get insanely good reviews on reputable review boards, and then turn out to be a load of half-assery once you finally give it a play. I never thought I'd jump on this bandwagon, but I truly believe games these days are theld at lower standards. This should change.."
