,Not Recommended,322500,21518901,"Posted: 28 February, 2016",all,Constable Poppycock,"I really wanted to like this game. The aesthetic looked really cool and the gameplay I saw looked awesome.Honestly though, it's really underwhelming. I finished the story in like 2 hours, maybe less. It's very, very pretentious. I'll explain at the bottom if you care about spoilers in a 2-hour game.The gameplay is alright, I guess. It gets very tedious, and it's often difficult to determine which bullets will actually hit you and which will not. I do somewhat enjoy the bullet travel time and having to calculate what you're going to hit, but some might dislike that.My biggest gripe with the gameplay is that the 'not moving unless you are' is actually an outright lie. Everything is moving, just very, very slowly. To the point where you can be shot while you're thinking because bullets move rather quick. There's also no crouch, so if someone fires a shotgun at shoulder height, there's actually no way to dodge if you're a little close. The best way I found of moving, since actually moving and shooting advances time very quickly was to jump and hold space wherever I went. Everyone responds at a proper speed in this manner, giving you time and ability to properly dodge bullets which you absolutely can't do on the ground.Cutting bullets in half with a katana also barely works. You can do one, maybe? But if someone has a machine gun or even a second person with a handgun behind them the swing time of the katana will guarantee you'll get hit by someone or something else.The endless mode is broken, too. Unless you wait 1-3 seconds after dying to see the 'your score' screen, the game won't actually store your score which is really, really obnoxious.The game actually feels kind of unfinished. I would've liked a more multidimensional story and more items--I understand the limitations of an indie team, but with what's in here doesn't feel like a $20 product. I have 6 hours clocked and I feel mostly done with the game. Maybe if I wanted to listen to a podcast I'd play, but if the selling point of the game is that it's a great time-waster while you're listening to a podcast, you're putting yourself in the same boat as free flash games.The biggest problem of all, is the COMPLETE LACK OF MUSIC. Everything feels dead and extremely uninteresting. The most lively thing in the game is a minigame where you chop a tree--because it actually has MUSIC. The absolute silence save for a robotic voice screaming SUPER HOT SUPER HOT when you finish a level and watch the replay is atrociously obnoxious. And the GIGANTIC ♥♥♥♥ING TEXT covering ANY AND ALL REPLAYS is, AGAIN, very, VERY annoying. Also, how do you edit replays? How do you upload them? Neither really worked for me. And there's no way to just download them as a file.TLDR;The game is rather pretentious, boring, and one dimensional, and definitely not worth $20. There is no music through 90% of the above advertised game, there are a rather limited set of maps, the 'campaign' is extremely short, and everything after that is 'challenges' and 'endless mode' which are on largely the same set of maps. And, lastly, it's hard to tell when you'll get shot.Game's got a little spirit though, I guess.Spoilers:I find the story very pretentious. For example, Spec Ops the Line handles the idea of 'stop playing, you're doing horrible violence' very very well. There's a decent story, and a lot of slow buildup to the twist. SUPERHOT basically tells you the twist in the first five minutes. And then it beats you over the head with it. You're told, basically from the start, to 'stop playing', in one form or another, and actually directly at the 1-hour mark, when the mysterious red text makes your proxy type 'I will not run SUPERHOT.exe again'. You can do that in a game that has a longer story. But when I paid $20 for your game LESS THAN AN HOUR AGO, the concept isn't that interesting, even if you tell me that the red people are real and 'bodies are disposable'."
