,Recommended,322500,21918007,"Posted: 19 March, 2016",all,ghost on the highway,"the following review will touch on some gameplay aspects that some people may consider spoilers; if you are sensitive to spoilers and wish to dive into the game without prior knowledge of how it will play, you might consider skipping this review (you might consider skipping it regardless of caring about spoilers or not, but w/e)superhot is a first person shooter whose main differential to other games in the genre is tying the running of time to your movements, meaning that the moment you stop moving, the enemies and the bullets already fired will essentially stop too (i say essentially because they still move, although on veeeeeeeeery slow motion).the game follows the ""one shot one kill"" school of design, meaning that there isn't a life bar or regenerating health i.e. the moment you get hit by one bullet, no matter on which part of your body, you will die, the same applying to the enemies.the arsenal of weapons is not particularly impressive, being composed of 1. melee weapons: a katana sword, something resembling a baseball bat and your fists (the only instance where you will need more than one hit to kill an enemy) and 2. some shooter staples: a pistol, a rifle, and a shotgun, but it gets the job done. additionally, you can throw various items found throughout the levels, as well as all the weapons, which will either kill the enemy (in the case of the katana sword) or stun them for a period of time (the other ones).around the middle of the game you will receive the ability to change bodies with any enemy, which will allow you to do some cool things, e.g. waiting for an enemy to fire against you, stop moving (thus essentially freezing the bullets during their trajectory) and then changing bodies with the enemy, which will lead you to safety while the red dude that fired at you gets shattered by the very bullets he fired mere moments earlier).there are not different kinds of enemies (i.e. you won't encounter blue, yellow or green dudes that are harder to fight or have more health), meaning you will be fighting red dudes from the first to the very last stage; difficulty increases, then, come from the different situations you are put in and the number of enemies you will face on a given level, as well as their weapons.each level is fairly short, meaning that after you have died enough time to more or less master a level you will be able to beat it in a matter of seconds.visually, the game is essentially monochromatic, with white being the dominating color, although pale blues and greys are also present; at first it reminded me of the visuals on mirror's edge, but it doesn't have the strong, vivid colors that dice's game uses to break the ""monotony"". i like this clean approach, but to some it may get tiresome and uninteresting.the campaign is fairly short, but the single player is expanded by a challenge mode (where you play through the game with a set of predetermined conditions, e.g. playing with the katana only, playing the game with each gun having only on bullet) and by a mode that seems to be essentially an endless wave kind of thing (admittedly, though, i haven't put much time on this one).there is also a little story, told through chat sessions, some small levels and interventions made by the system (as well as featuring some meta elements), but it seemed kind of secondary to me.all in all, it's a nice game with an interesting, unique mechanic that i would say deserves to be played, even if you wish to wait for a steam sale to buy it cheaper."
,Recommended,322500,22464338,"Posted: 16 April, 2016",all,Toasty,It’s the most innovative shooter I’ve played in years.
