,Recommended,322500,21543371,"Posted: 29 February, 2016",all,InsaneFox (InsaneFox),"After a good 7 hours of playtime, I must say, the gameplay is phenoenal and unlike anything I've ever seen before, it's done well, there are verry few times that you'll die and say ""Now that was just bull.""  Even when it's an enemy that comes out of nowhere, this game makes you feel like you are ultimately responsible.  The only problem with the game mechanics is that some of the walls and corners seem to have inflated hitboxes, so bullets will strike against corners they wouldn't have hit.HOWEVER, this game's story almost convinced me to give the game a negative review for two broad reasons:1:  The story is out of place, slow, and interupts the fast paced action.2:  The type of story was very poorly executed.Before you read this rant, the story only covers about 2 hours of gameplay at most, so the other five hours I played at the time of writing this review was spent slicing through bullets with a katana, throwning katanas through people and catching them on the other side, and punching red dudes in the face.  Those first two hours were actually the tutorial.As for the story:  You're playing some game you're not supposed to be playing on an old DOS terminal, you pretend to type into a box, and then press buttons you're asked to press, and occasionally you're rewarded with the sweet gameplay.  Think of the broad concept of Pony Island, except strip down all the interactive elements of the actual story and replace the pony jumping game with Super Hot's bullet hell, and make the game as condecending as physically possible.  For that type of story to work, the gameplay cannot be more engaging than the story, it doesn't have to be terrible, but it needs to be the means to the end and not the center focus of the game's value.  Not to mention that you need to let the player try to resist the system/overlord/condescending story that interrupted the awesome gameplay, or else the story is just boring.Now, all that doesn't sound too bad, right, not nearly bad enough to bring down an otherwise amazing game and earn a negative review?  Well, it was one line in particular that nearly convinced me to write a negative review.  When I thought that this story couldn't get any more condescending, that it's tone of ""We own you now, do whatever we say, slave,"" it uttered this line and ended the tutorial ""Now go tell all your friends to play this game, tell them it's an innovative shooter and it's amazing."" as ""recruting.""  This might work in a game about the story part of it, if it's delivered when I feel like I've won, when I feel like I've finished the game, or at the very least, have experienced the most fun part of the game and WASN'T TALKED DOWN TO BY A CONDESCENDING SYSTEM/OVERLORD/ADMINISTRATOR, but after having sat through what is by far the worst story in a game I otherwise enjoy, I really wanted to click no, I really wanted to tell people it wasn't worth their time, just to say ""Hey, ♥♥♥♥ you"" to the system/overlord/admin who thinks that their constant interruptons are somehow better than the act of slicing through bullets with a katana, and has the balls to not just ask me recomend it to my friends, but to say it's ""innovative.""  (Yeah, the game is pretty innovative, but really, don't tell me what words to use when describing it to my friends.)So, is the game still good despite having the most condescending and pretentious story I've ever dealt with?  Do not underestimate the amount of fun you can have with a katana.Yeah, this game is worth $15, maybe $20... but I've had more fun with this thing than most $60 games that are out now, so, not complaining about the price."
