,Recommended,322500,21489173,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Caessa,"An absolutely amazing game. Unique mechanics combined with... with... alright it's the unique mechanics.It's a lot of fun, it feels like a cross between a shooter w/ travel (i.e. Battlefield instead of COD where the bullets and projectiles have travel time) and a puzzle game/bullet hell. It's engaging and just hard enough to challenge yet not hard enough for me to rage since, even if I die, I ♥♥♥♥ing died in fashion and a blaze of glory! The gameplay is utterly satisfying, especially the killcam at the end when you can see your entire spree of murder! It's awe-inspiring how 10 minutes of meticulous planning and work ends up being a mere 10-12 seconds ""IRL"".Graphics: It's own geometry style graphics. Nothing to write home about it's very minimalistic so I'll say this is a neutral whether it is a pro or con. You decide. For me I felt it was perfect simply due to the fact that your enemies crumble into pieces before you in a way ""real world"" like graphics can't convey. For me this was slightly positive but I can understand if such a simple graphical style isn't to your liking.Gameplay: Mostly positive as I've stated. What would I change? More weapon variety in my opinion. With a game that literally slows time to a crawl, different guns with miniscule differences would feel completely different and completely change how you go about beating a mission. Touch up the killcams at the end. The animations feel too... flitty since they were designed for bullet-time I feel like the camera at the end sometimes does not feel as epic as it could. A small complaint since it still feels fricken awesome!Story: Simple story, nothing to write home about but it is captivating. It is only 2-3 hours long, shorter if you're actually good at the game unlike me. Is this a con? To many, yes. To me? Not so much... I didn't care about the story all too much, I just wanted to kill people in bullet-time with a computer monitor and coffee mugs. The story detracted me from these awesome moments. I just wanted to go from corpse to corpse, gun to gun, coffee mug to katana. I was relieved, personally, when I reached the end and unlocked challenges and endless mode. THAT's what I wanted to play.Price: It's  20 some dollars for a unique, fun experience. I think it's worth it. I've gotten more enjoyment so far (only 2 or 3 hours in so far) than I have from many 60 dollar titles.♥♥♥♥ I love this game..."
,Recommended,322500,21490259,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,NotSoBrown,"Super sexy, love it! The game is super interesting and I am so happy to see the improvements from the prototype from years back! Definitely recommend it, there are some good twists that will keep pulling you back in."
,Recommended,322500,21494023,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,camycamera,"SUPERHOT is a game where time moves only when you do. It is an action FPS/puzzler game that first started out as a prototype that a lot of people played a few years ago (and you can still play it to this day) and loved so much that the developers of SUPERHOT released a kickstarter for it, and now, this is that game.And just like the original demo/prototype, it's damn awesome, and it takes what made the original prototype great and expands on it to prefection. The aesthetic, while simple, is quite pleasing, especially when you punch/hit/slice/shoot the red glass men and watch them shatter against the white background behind them. The videos on the store page do quite a good job of showing off what the game looks like, and in short, It makes you feel badass.This is the game you want if you want to dodge bullets matrix style from a guy point blank, punch him, take his gun while he is reacting from the punch, blow his head off, shoot the guy next to him while still doging bullets, throw your gun at the next guy, pick up a katana, slice an oncomming bullet in half (yes you can do that and more, I'll put a few tips down below), cut the guy you threw the gun at  in half, and then throw the katana at the last guy behind you. All that, in just a couple of seconds.It's just great, and in fact it is one of the few games that I have bought on day 1. Yes, I'm one of those (sensible and patient) people who buys games way after they've been released at 50 or 75% off.Now with those such game mechanics, you might think this game is easy, but, at least in my experience, it's not. You're gonna die a lot, especially on the challenge modes which change up the gameplay rules and freshen up the experience, as bullets/melee weapons kill you in one hit. Or maybe its because I am too zealous when playing this game sometimes and forget to stand still and get shot in the back in the process a lot of the time. The game makes you think back to other shooters and what we take for granted these days in those games.So it really saddens me to see a couple of ""most helpful"" reviews being negative, pointing out how short the campaign is (I beat it in about 2-3 hours), and thus saying that the game is not worth the asking price of 25 bucks (at the time of writing it is 10% off at $22.50). And I'm going to adress that. First off, this isn't a game that you play the campaign and put it down forever, and that's it. The campaign is not even HALF of the game. It might as well be the tutorial for the rest of the game, I'd even argue. As you can probably see from those negative reviews, they've only played 2-3 hours (the length of the campaign), then come here and post a negative review without bothering to try anything else that the game has to offer.As I said, this isn't the game you play only for the campaign, this is the type of game you play for the core gameplay experience, and you won't get all of that core experience from the campaign alone, not by a long shot. After you beat the campaign, you unlock various endless and challenge modes. Endless modes are self explanatory, and within those endless modes there are variations such as time limits and stuff like that, and then there's challenges. Challenges put a spin on top of the core gameplay. There's modes to unlock from Katana only, to a ""Ghost"" mode where you can only hotswitch (possess enemies by teleporting into them) and one hit kill enemies with punches but can't pick up any weapons or objects. There is so much variety in these challenge and endless modes alone, you can get countless of hours into the game, to make it well worth the asking price.I got 2-3 hours out of the game's campaign, but I have gotten a further 8 or so hours from the challenge modes alone, and I plan to put in even more hours into it.There's even loads of secrets to find throughout the game if that's your type of thing. This game is packed full of content, it's just a shame that it presented itself with the campaign first, and people thought ""is that it?"" and then went on to spread negative reviews of it as a result.But anyway, now that's out of the way, here's some actual criticism (sorta) that will hopefully be sorted out with time:The ""Killstagram"" website where you can quickly record and upload your gameplay while in the game to show off your mad skillz or because it just looked cool, is in beta, and so it doesn't work properly. I've used the in-game record function alot, and I can't find my countless recordings. Once they are recorded, they are sent off to the website under some random name rather than mine. You can make an account but that doesn't work yet, nor does the option to view your own replays. I did manage to find one of mind though randomly,Here it is. I believe they have switched over to GIF rather than youtube now, which is why mine's on youtube, I'm not entirely sure. But for now, the site is a bit broken right now and could use some tweaks.It would be awesome if this game had a map editor, apparently it was on the kickstarter goals but they didn't reach it. Hopefully, with this game's success, we'll see it patched in somehow, because right now we've only got the game's vanilla maps. There's quite a few of them, but it would be awesome to see more, not just from the community but from the developers themselves. It would make this game's replay value skyrocket.Basically more stuff: There aren't a lot of weapon/enemy types etc, I don't think that's a bad thing and some even argue that the simplicity of that is fine, which I can agree with, but it would be cool to have a lot more variation on things to use. Hopefully modders will be able to add in a bunch of stuff if this game gets that support from modders and the developers. Mind you, I'm not saying that what the game offers in terms of stuff is bad, not by any stretch, but in the case of this game, I think more stuff would do nothing but benefit this game greatly I think. Maybe we'll get that in the sequel, like with DOOM 2 that went insane and expanded DOOM 1 greatly.It would be cool to have a crouch button, so we can properly do a Matrix-stlye dodge and watch bullets fly above our heads as we duck.Tips/things to note when playing:As you might have read above, you can cut bullets in half with the Katana. Yes, it is as awesome as it sounds. And there's an achievement for it.On top of that, you can shoot bullets with your own bullets. It is more trickier to bull of then you think, mind you. And yes, there's an achievement for that too.Pressing space will make you jump, of course. But HOLDING space will make you jump, AND slow down time while you are in the air (also holding space while falling will slow down time as well). The game tells you this in the campaign, but I didn't figure this out until after beating the campaign. It completely changed the way I played, Jumping on and over obsticals and enemies, shooting and dodging bullets in mid air, all that great stuff.You can jump on people's head to kill them. And of course, there's a Mario-themed achievement for that as well.You can kill two dudes with one Katana if you throw them at two people standing in front of eachother. And at this point I'm just telling you how to get achievements, sorry about that.You can get the red guys to shoot their own guys (on accident, of course). It is useful when you need a body shield, or just need to kill two birds with one stone. It is hard though, and there's no achievement for it.So there we have it. Buy this game if you like this sort of stuff or just vaguely like the idea, and it'll be a steal on sale. And like I said before, don't just play the campaign and drop it and then complain about it, because that's not the sort of game that this is and is not what all the game has to offer."
