,Recommended,322500,21482529,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Periapse,"It's the Matrix in pure video game form, in more ways than the obvious. It feels like a bullet time gun-fu movie and a Kojima game all at once. Some people feel like it's lacking in content, but I disagree. The story mode is short, no doubt, but the game hardly ends there. There are tons of challenge modes, endless horde maps and so on, and it actually doesn't need much more to it than that because the mechanics are just so darn brilliant. Would you criticise chess for being feature poor because the boards are always an eight by eight grid? No, because that's not the point. Superhot is so original and well crafted that it doesn't need any extra padding to be worth your time and money.The devs focused on what really mattered. But as if to make sure nobody could accuse their game of being feature poor, the devs have snuck in loads of goodies. There are a lot of smaller mini-features which add immensely to the character of the game. So much creativity and love has been put into superhot, as evidenced by loads of extra goodies that I don't want to spoil for you - for a start, just explore the options below the primary buttons in the main menu.TL;DR The mechanics are so brilliant that it does not need any extra feature padding to be worth your money. It's the most innovative shooter I've played in years."
