,Recommended,322500,21487745,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,StevenSeagal,"What I ininitally thought was an entertaining gimick has really matured into a great blend of innovative gameplay and interesting story from its first demo days. I love the interface the game is presented with and the overall style of the gameplay itself. The story mode is short, but in reality is the few hours-long tutorial for the endless modes and challenges that unlock upon completion. That's where the real game begins.As far as the story mode goes, it's actually quite interesting and engaging for a game that I was expecting to be just about slicing red dudes with katanas and matrix-style bullet dodges. It's just thought-provoking enough to provide a layer of abstract substance on a game that would otherwise be just fine if it was pure action and no story. Icing on the cake, if you will.The post singleplayer features range between endless survival modes and extra challenges on top of the single player levels. The endless mode is incredibly fun and the variations on it, including limits of in-game time or limits on real-world time are also very interesting from a puzzle perspective.SUPERHOT is a great game. Some might think that the game is too short to warrant a higher than $20 pricetag, but that's not where the core of the gameplay is. I can see myself spending so many more hours on the endless and challenge modes than the singleplayer campaign. It's worth every second and every penny."
