,Recommended,322500,21488951,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Patrician,"SuperHot a great little game that'll take you 2-3 hours to beat the main campaign. While I recommend it, if you're not sure you'll love this game already I'd wait for a sale. It's absolutely worth $15, but $25 may be a bit much if you don't have much cash to spend.While it's true that the campaign is 2-3 hours long, the truth is that it's more of a tutorial. After you beat the story, plenty of new challenge modes unlock for you to play. While I'd prefer they be unlocked from the beginning, this means that, if you enjoy the base gameplay gimmick enough, this game has PLENTY of content to justify its initial asking price. Just because it isn't narrative-focused or considered part of the campaign doesn't mean that it isn't worthwhile content. If you enjoy the time-stopping gameplay of SuperHot, you will find a lot of content here.As for the story, it really isn't anything special. It really does come off as pretentious (if you've played Pony Island, it really gives off that same exact vibe), and frankly I was just waiting for the sections of story to be over so I can go back to playing. It serves as a good preamble for the hours I plan on investing into the challenges and endless mode. A lot of people seem rather irate that the game doesn't have many weapons to play with, and while more would have been appreciated, the weapons we do have serve themselves well. They all have a learning curve to use, and they all work well enough to keep things fresh.If I did have one suggestion for the devs, it would be to enable the game for modding support or provide a level editor. I can see glorious fan-made levels being made here, and it would be a shame to see that potential squandered. It would also help people swallow the $25 asking price.The gameplay is tricky, super satisfying, and rewarding to master. It really does feel like playing a scene in The Matrix. It's a super unique gimmick that I'd love to see expanded in a sequel. As for right now, though, SuperHot still remains a game I recommend, if only to experience what people claim to be the most innovative FPS ever."
