,Recommended,322500,21486681,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Sanny,"For more reviews, and a link to a short gameplay video, head over here:https://probablysanny.wordpress.com/The concept behind this game is simple; You kill red guys, and time only moves when you do. Actually, time still moves very slowly when you stay still, but whatever. There are very few weapons in the game, but it doesn't feel like any more need to be added. Each weapon has it's own role: pistols are slow but reliable, rifles are dangerous to use, but powerful (they fire multiple bullets per trigger pull, and time speeds up while firing), shotguns act as you would expect, and melee weapons are good for hitting things with. This simplicity of design permeates SUPERHOT; the game never tries to do more than it needs to, and this works to its benefit. The simple acting of shooting things feels incredibly good. You can shoot bullets out of the air with other bullets, and if the shrapnel is close enough to an enemy, they will be stunned and drop their weapon. That is pretty damn cool.You wouldn't notice it at first glance, but as you play through the game, you will quickly realize that it's actually a series of real-time puzzles, in a similar vein to Hotline Miami. The game requires you to make quick decisions and pay close attention to your environment, especially sound. In later levels, you will probably need to play multiple times to figure out the best way to deal with a situation.I only have two real issues with the gameplay. Sometimes it can be hard to discern whether a bullet is going to hit you or not, which is especially frustrating knowing that you can only take one hit. And the game has punch and pick-up bound to the same key. Sometimes you will go to grab a weapon out of the air, only to find you clicked a few pixels to the left, punch an enemy, and die because you wasted a few precious seconds. The second problem doesn't come up very often, but it is very frustrating when it does. The reason these problems are so annoying is that they are the only problems I noticed; if they weren't present, the gameplay would be perfect, as far as I'm concerned.There isn't a lot to say about the visuals in SUPERHOT, its very minimalist. If you've seen one screenshot of the game, you pretty much know whether you like the look or not.The music isn't really worth mentioning either, as it doesn't stand out too much, so I'll just breeze past that.The menus in SUPERHOT are presented in the form of a DOS-esque interface. There are plenty of interesting things to find, and little hidden jokes; I think I spent the first 30 minutes of playtime just exploring the menu.I thought the story was a little predictable, but it was interesting enough for what it was. I can't talk too much about it without spoiling, however, so I'll just leave it there.The game automatically records your playthrough of every level for later viewing. This seems like a cool idea at first, but I felt the execution was a bit lacking. Although the game looks fine in slow motion, it doesn't feel quite right in real time. And the game constantly chants and covers half the screen with the words SUPER-HOT, seemingly to distract from the weird looking animations and general lack of any other audio. You can disable this by pressing 7 on the Numpad, which is useful, but makes the lack of polish on the replays painfully obvious.SUPERHOT's story is fairly short, but it has and endless mode, and several challenge modes to complete. If you're the sort of player that is concerned about longevity, they've got you covered.Although the game has a lot of flaws, I'd still recommend it to almost anyone. The only real issue might be the pricetag but, after playing, I don't feel that its acutally that far off the mark. It's such a unique experience-and the core gameplay is almost perfect-, that it still managed to impress me."
