,Recommended,322500,34670452,Posted: 1 September,all,tagenar,"I really wish steam had a neutral rating.  This isn't a bad game, but at just 2 hours it is incredibly small for the price.  It has one concept (time only moves when you move, which isn't actually true; enemies and bullets still move even when standing still, just very slowly), but it doesn't do much with it.  The campaign levels are short, and the challenge levels all happen in the same arena.  The tiny story tries to be artsy and profound but comes across as just vague nonsense.  I have a feeling it was made for the VR platform and a lot is lost when playing on PC.The game is also headache-inducing because the environment is predominately white, and there is very little to break that up.  Movement is slow and herky-jerky, which makes manuvering painfully frustrating, but it's required because levels are designed so you can't take two steps without being in someone's line of fire, and the game requires precision movement to dodge enemies and bullets.  The levels are disconnected and have nothing to do with one another, which doesn't help the story at all because it doesn't feel like a coherent whole.The developers had a decent idea, and I think it could have been better if the story mode had been better.  Without that, everything is kinda pointless.  It's not bad as a proof-of-concept, as the gameplay is challenging, satisfying, and stands on its own, but a single gimmick can only take a game so far."
