,Recommended,322500,21540395,"Posted: 28 February, 2016",all,i love the work on it can do,"I was spurred into making this review to counteract the toxic contingent of gamers that think it's too expensive.It's not, it's worth the $25 at launch, and it will continue to be. It's certainly in contention for my game of the year and the amount of time that I have spent thusfar and will likely spend into the future on SUPERHOT make it well worth such an amount of money to me.It's a high concept idea for a game - time moves when you move. But it elevates this fairly simple element with its stark visual presentation, its sinister narrative, and its sense of style that it maintains throughout the campaign, such as it is.It took me around two and a half hours or so to finish what comprises the 'story', with some levels taking more tries than others. Since that time, though, I've been combing through the other modes. The Katana-only Challenge, for instance, poses an interesting break in the flow that the game has reinforced up until that point, thereby forcing you to rethink your approaches with a certain amount of caution that you might not have considered if you happened to be predisposed as I was to stealing guns from people and blowing up their friends.Additionally, there are time-attack and endless modes, and possibly yet more that I have yet to unlock, so I think I'll be spending a bit more time yet on it.In the end, you're going to have to decide whether the price is worth it or not, but it's not relevent to the content of the game and, as such, it can only be seen as disappointing that people are so willing to disparage something not because it isn't good, but because it isn't goodenough.There should be no place for such a thing in this review system. The craft and time that were put into this game, stretching all the way back to when it was first conceived during the 7DFPS jam, are incredibly apparent—immanent with the cracking sound of every bullet and shattering cluster of red polygons."
