76561197969782921,Recommended,322500,21501311,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Flatline,"In Response to the ""2 hours of content"" nonsense:The main ""story"" is about two hours, if you rush through it. But really, the core game is its gameplay mechanic (the enjoyment of perfectly choreographed slow-motion fights) and once you complete the story, you are given the following unlocked gameplay modes:* Countless challenge modes, such as ""katana only"", a ghost mode in which you can swap bodies at will, a mode that lets you play the entire game in the style of its original browser-based prototype, speed run modes, and many others that I haven't even unlocked yet.* An Endless mode, with many maps to unlock as you go along.* Level selection, so you can go back and do any of the old maps again (and you can always reset the story if you like).* A secret thing on every map.Is this a long, narrative-driven experience? No. It's a truly hypnotic, oddly relaxing (slightly unsettling) experience in which the core premise is one of puzzle-solving.The puzzle being:""You're in a room with four guys, and they all have guns, and you have a 90s-era brick-style cell phone. How do you kill them all?""The puzzle being:""You're in a server room inexplicably filled with shotguns and assault rifles and men who are now running to grab them, and you have nothing but fists. How do you kill them all?""The puzzle being:""You're in a bar, the bartender has a shotgun, and you have a bottle. How do you kill them all?""The answer to all these puzzles being:""HOWEVER YOU LIKE, SO LONG AS IT LOOKS SUPER HOT."""
