76561198062369107,Recommended,322500,21498296,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Dragonfly_Chaser,"Did you enjoy the frantic gunplay and cover-bouncing of hotline miami but were frustrated by not being able to plan your moves? Superhot's hook mechanic of time moving only when you move is not itself a new idea, but it's expertly applied here.As time stops for you in between every shot, step and punch, your enemies have moved and every time you slow to plan your next move, you must reevaluate the scene over again. Allowing the player time to think in this kind of 'one and you're done' action setting is a golden idea, and the execution doesn't fall into the pitfall of 'bullet time' that many other games do. You have all the same faculties as your enemies, you can't move faster than them, and they'll predict your movements to shoot or flank to your predicted position, the advantage you have is planning time, while still giving you the feeling that your reactions are instantaneous and fluid.Superhot has a nice balanced bite to it's difficulty as well- it isn't the manic 50% luck of hotline miami but it will still push you to be quick on the uptake as enemies are no slouches when it comes to trying to put you out.The aesthetic of the game suits the mood- everything is colour-washed and minimalist, with an eerie, sometimes calm feeling throughout, much to a counterpoint of hotline miami's neon insanity.Sound effects are crisp and defined, a shot from any weapons sounds and feels weighty, and all sound effects distort to the tune of your time-warping excellently.Recommended for those who like their lethal action with a bit of brainwork involved."
