,Recommended,322500,21487140,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,bobert awful (F+),"SUPERHOT is ♥♥♥♥ing bonkers. SUPERHOT would be a Jackie Chan movie, if Jackie Chan was really into cyberpunk and had seen The Matrix a thousand times. It's a game where you beat up a dude in a bathroom stall, then you pick up the bottle in the corner of the restroom, use it to glass the face of the red dude coming in for a♥♥♥♥♥♥ and after all that, you see the bartender with his shotgun in his hands, and you dare to pick up one of the billard balls on the pool table, and then you dare even harder to chuck it at his ♥♥♥♥ing head. It's ♥♥♥♥ing wonderful improvisation combat in the form of a puzzle FPS.The game does a fantastic job telling you all the basics without having to explain it to you through its use of colors and visual language. The scenery is white-grey, things you kill with are colored black, red dudes are bad and must be punished, use black things to kill red dudes. Even if you haven't played many FPS games, you'll know instantly what's going on, allowing you to focus on the puzzle side of the game - the puzzle of how you kill those red dudes. And even then, the game manages to pull out some novel takes on its formula - the Elevator Pitch level is a ♥♥♥♥ing great take on using your fists to get the upper hand on three people with guns pointed at you point-blank.Some whiners say that the three-hour campaign is too little story for $25. But they're also ignoring the wealth of challenges, the Endless mode, and the various secrets built into the game. And even if we're judging the game entirely by its entire campaign - SUPERHOT has a really well done, solid campaign, one that hits its mark, never misses a beat, and knows exactly where to start and when to quit. I'd rather have a campaign that is three hours long, artfully paced, knowing how best to deliver its thrills, and is concluded properly rather than a campaign that takes fifteen hours, wears out its welcome, and farts out a conclusion that makes me never want to play the game again after I'm done. Have we learned nothing from ♥♥♥♥ing Portal, a game that is almost flawless and just two hours long? Meeting an arbitrary goal of how much time your game consumes does not make a game good.The only real complaint I have is that I don't know if the stuff between the campaign levels is going to hold up for me down the line? I imagine myself old and toothless, and I'll scream WHAT IS THIS DOS♥♥♥♥♥♥ I NEED TO KILL THE RED PEOPLE. And then I'll throw my cellphone at the TV and have to be sent to work in the salt mines on the Plutonian Asteroid and Old Folks' Home. Being old is going to suck, but at least I'll always have Superhot!"
