,Recommended,322500,21511701,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Banta,SPOILER:The song at the end is badass. 10/10
,Recommended,322500,21511967,"Posted: 27 February, 2016",all,Grizzly,"I've been watching Superhot pretty closely ever since the demo they released back in 2013. I'm not sure how the dev time was so long, but I'm happy to say the final product has met my expectations very well, and that's without any extra updates or features added after launch (if there are any pls say yes devs)So what is Superhot? It's like... a very fast-paced shooter based entirely around playing slowly. Sounds strange at first, and that's exactly what Superhot is. I feel the best way sell how good this game is, is by telling you firsthand instead of trying to describe it.To put it bluntly, Superhot is probably the only game that lets you jump around the corner of an office cubicle in slow motion, then launch a katana from your hand while sailing through the air to pierce two people straight through the chest and literally turn them into a f'king kebab.Superhot is probably the only game where I can kill a large group of heavily armed enemies just by throwing bottles and glasses at them.Superhot is probably the only game where I can throw my weapon at somebody to make them drop their weapon, then sail through the air, grab their weapon in slow motion, fly directly out a nearby window, turn in a full 180 and then fire back at the person I stole the weapon from while sailing out a window to my death.Superhot allows for so much freedom in how you play. Whether you sit back and slowly and methodically kite each enemy towards you while you whittle them down slowly, or you go cartwheeling through a big maze of bullets defending yourself with random clutter items left on the floor and impaling everyone with a katana, it's pretty strategic. Each level pits you against a certain amount of ""Red Dudes"", who you fight. You can use whatever you want to in order to defeat them, and it's that freedom to dive around the room, dodging bullets in slow motion that makes Superhot so hectic and fun.It's also got a story, and quite a trippy one at that. The main game only lasts about 2 hours, which is hardly worth the 20 euro price tag, but Superhot also comes with two other modes, both of which are filled with extra content. So far, I'm over 10 hours into the game and still nowhere near bored, and keep in mind, I'm only playing this at 20 frames. If I can play a fast paced game that requires a high framerate at 20 frames and it keeps drawing me back into it every time I try to do something more productive, you can assume the game is addictive.The only cons of Superhot are the hit detection. Man, the hit detection. For a game that requires such surgical precision, it's surprisingly bad. I can't seemingly fit between two bullets, even though the gap between them is definitely big enough. I throw a katana at someone but it goes right through them. I throw a clutter item at someone to stun them and it just bounces off them without having any effect. The hit detection needs an improvment.Other than that, the spawn points on Endless mode are very messy. When an enemy spawns, they'll go through a short ""fade-in"" animation. The problem is, you can't see them during the animation but they can still fire at you. To add to this, enemies can spawn directly behind you, and there's nothing worse than losing a killstreak because someone suddenly appeared behind you with no warning, and then just filled your back with lead.Other than those two small gripes, the game is perfect for anyone who enjoys bullet time, shooters and fast-paced, hectic gameplay.*SUPERHOT IS THE MOST INNOVATIVE SHOOTER I'VE PLAYED IN YEARS!"
