,Recommended,322500,21492123,"Posted: 26 February, 2016",all,Shooter like YoungPappy,The product child of the original flash game.
,Not Recommended,322500,34075003,Posted: 6 August,all,General Kass,"SUPERHOT proves that innovative and fun are not mutually exclusive.I’m sure you already know the premise here. A first person shooter where time moves as you do. You may notice that 90% of reviews of this game use the exact phrase “the most innovate shooter I’ve played in years.” It’s hard to say if those are sincere opinions since you'll learn that line is synonymous with classics like “would you kindly” and “the cake is a lie.” It’s a disingenuous meme that halts actual discussion about the game.As I vaguely allude to the story, I’ll say this: I thought it was really predictable. Here’s a challenge: Play the game up until you get thrown back to the main menu for the first time. Then write down what you think the story is. Odds are, you’re probably very close if not on the nose.So here’s where we get into the gameplay itself. The gameplay is OK. It’s very very ok. Although the entire game relies on a time mechanic, SUPERHOT isn’t as good as other games’ time mechanics. A number of needless pain points arise because of the time mechanic. For example, doing an action (like picking up a weapon) jumps time forward 0.30 seconds, while normal walking moves time 0.10 seconds a step. Bending over to pick up that pistol can have you immediately killed because not only does it move time forward 0.30 seconds, you're also moving the camera down and then back up and then on an enemy, all of which waste time. To put all this into context, a lot of speedrun missions have a par time of 4.00 seconds. Just picking up a weapon uses 1/13th of that total time.This should not have been a first person shooter. Neither the art style or the gameplay complement a first person shooter. Why? First of all, your hitbox is bigger than your screen. Bullets will clearly whiz above your head and then immediately kill you. There’s no crouch button and no way to know if you actually dodged the bullet until it kills you. This could have been solved with a third person shooter where you can see your hitbox.Another pain point of the FPS is that a lot of missions in the second half drop you in the center of the action. This means that enemies will spawn from all directions. But wait a second, time moves as you do. So spinning the camera 180 degrees moves time forward 4-5 seconds. Again, there’s no crouch feature; you can’t take cover behind that pool table. Add to this that enemies make a sound when they die and when they fire their guns, but they don’t make a sound when they appear. Due to the game’s minimalist style, there’s almost no sound at all. This means that you often won’t know enemies spawned behind you until your corpse hits the floor.SUPERHOT isn’t a puzzle game as many would have you believe. It’s more like Hotline Miami if you died every time you looked behind you. Yet every single problem in the last two paragraphs could be solved if this game was third person. With a third person camera we could see the enemies coming without breaking the flow and you could still have a minimalist and mostly soundless art direction BUT allow players to inform themselves about the environment.Also, I have to laugh and laugh and laugh that the game's description calls itself ""polished."" Bullets, especially from shotguns will often go through walls. Don't believe me? Try the train level. If the hitboxes on the PC are poorly defined and the hitboxes on the buildings are poorly definied, then the devs still have a lot of work to do, even a 1.5 years after release.I won’t spoil, but the game doesn’t even properly use its full arsenal. Toward the end of the game, you’re granted a game-changing feature. The problem is that they take it away for the finale. To understand what an objectively bad piece of game design that is, think about how most games teach. You learn how to play and you’re tested on that element. Then you learn some more and you use what you learned before with the new. SUPERHOT’s finale is like spending a week studying for a math test. The assigned homework is ¾ multiplication and ¼ division. Then the day of the test comes and none of the questions mention division. That’s SUPERHOT.For a $20 game with a 2-hour run time, I can’t recommend SUPERHOT to anyone, despite it’s positive reputation. The gunplay is more irritating than innovate due to the previously mentioned design choices that make the game more trial and error than puzzle. The story kept me going, but ultimately disappointed. But hey, at least we got some memes.If you like paying too much for too little, by all means, buy SUPERHOT."
