,Recommended,322500,22614334,"Posted: 24 April, 2016",all,Groxworld1,"Originally my intention for this review was to complete all of the challenge and endless mode, but after countless meaningless results and a loss of determination; I began to decide against it. This review is mainly based from my experience from the story mode. Also, a minor disclaimer. I have been waiting for this game for three years, ever since the 7DFPS challenge. So some bias is to be expected.SUPERHOT is an FPS where time moves when you move (though you still breathe, so you can't completely stop time), and as of right now; is my favorite game of this year. SUPERHOT's main mechanic of time manipulation leads to what is easy and fun to get into, but is hard and challenging to master. But outside of the mechanic itself, the level design is also very well done (at least in the story mode). The weapons have just enough variety for it to feel different, and with the addition of the time manipulation mechanic; the difference becomes more noticeable. There are a few subtle things they added that really helped how much better the game plays, but I'll just leave them be to cut short on time.The story of SUPERHOT itself isn't exactly very impressive, if not a bit lackluster. Some of the things it pulled simply did not work because of some pacing issues, but it honestly isn't worth dwelling on. If anything, the lack of length in SUPERHOT is a bit of a mixed issue for me. It's as short as it should be, sure; but there's this feeling that the game is too short. The length may raise a few eyebrows here and there, however for those who would like a strong new innovation; SUPERHOT wins a strong recommendation.So in short, SUPERHOT is a game with some strong innovations (and a very beautiful aesthetic), with a somewhat lackluster length. And with the current price tag, there's obviously going to be some people who are against buying SUPERHOT."
76561198024972303,Recommended,322500,22737906,"Posted: 1 May, 2016",all,The Golf War,"Superhot is one of the most challenging games I have played in a while. Basically you just have to kill all the red guys in the level. But get hit once, you have to restart the level. Once you complete the story mode, you unlock endless mode and challenge mode and can also start up a particular level from the story. The challenges add to the game's replayability by making you rethink a map you already completed.With that being said, the only thing I didn't like about the game was the story. I honestly could have cared less for it and the game would be no different if you removed the story entirely from the game.I'd give this game a solid 4/5"
