76561198046468600,Not Recommended,322500,26337102,"Posted: 31 October, 2016",all,Zero-Five,"Things like this are a crying shame.  This is nothing more than an extended tutorial.This game has an interesting mechanic, and that's pretty much all there is to it.  It is absurdly short, where I played it through to completion in under two hours, and beat a bunch of other challenges under an hour thereafter.  Not all of them, mind you, but enough to say that I've played most of what this game has to offer, and it's not much.If you watched the videos of this game, you've probably seen a full quarter of the gameplay available.  The levels are very short and confined.  Despite this, some levels are actually very fun - one where you start off surrounded by three people in an elevator and you have to figure out how to best all of them without one of the others shooting you first, or the elevator doors opening and revealing two more dudes shooting at you.There's also a pretty, ahem, bad*** moment early on where you start a level with a demand ""Come with us"".  Then a few seconds later, the screen flashed, ""HOW.  ABOUT.  NO!"", and you start the level with a gun pointed at your head and you have to fight your way through a bunch of dudes.  It's a moment that made me grin and fistpump in the air, but that was the only such moment this entire game provided.I think a more experienced development team could have hashed out a much, much longer campaign, and perhaps gave more nuance to the game, more mechanics, and so forth.  About halfway through the game you get a body-switching power, and it's almost entirely optional to use.  It's useful, yes, but a creative dev team could have dreamed up a level where you had to body switch with a guy on a balcony to keep fighting, because there was no other way to get up there (for example).  But really, the mechanics in this game are never fully realized.I said in the beginning that this game is an extended tutorial.  A cool mechanic like this is akin to things in other, more developed games, where they grant you a new power and some easy time to mess around with it, before flinging you back into the main game to use it in a dozen different ways.  This game never gets past the tutorial phase with it.  Too short, too easy, too simplistic, a waste of an awesome pair of concepts (bullet-time as a norm, and body-switching), and a waste of money.If you get a chance to get the game for free, it's definitely worth playing then.  But that's the problem here - this game is a neat and quick diversion but nothing worth paying for."
