76561197993622903,Recommended,322500,28263100,"Posted: 8 December, 2016",all,Vital_Shot,"SUPERHOT is proof of what can happen when a small, indi development team puts out what is essentially a labor of love: they create a product that easily competes with the big boys, those AAA developers with all the money and the huge offices and marketing and labor pools...SUPERHOT has breathed life into the ailing FPS genre. It brings original mechanics, notably its ""bullet time"" system to freshen up a genre that has simply become: ""guy get gun, go blow things up, BOOM"". Its plot, like its graphics, seems simple at first, but as the player advances through the various ""cracked"" levels, a more far more interesting, layered, and sinister plot begins to show itself.The graphics themselves are pretty... They're simple polygons of red, black, and white, but they are utilized extremely well . The game flows smoothly, and I don't once find myself wishing for something more ""realistic.""The gameplay itself is easy to pick up, but hard to master, particularly as more and more mechanics are added, and there are even a few mechanics hidden, just waiting to be discovered by accident, or by particularly creative players (It's a me! Mario!).If I had any gripe... it would be that the game mechanics feel almost TOO simple I love bullet time, and I love being able to pull off matrix-like moves, but let me do more of it. Let me run on walls. Let me crouch and lean to avoid bullets. Let me do what I'm accustomed to doing in an FPS, but do it with more style.The variety of weapons could also use a bit of work. Maybe add in an explosive or two... rather than either every gun having bullets or every melee object simply being there to throw... This game is amazing, and it has TONS of room to grow. Now if you'll excuse me, I want to dig some more into this mystery.SUPER HOTSUPER HOTSUPER HOTSUPER HOT"
